</ul>
</div></div> <!-- /node-inner, /node -->
<div id="node-99" class="node node-type-story node-promoted node-teaser build-mode-teaser"><div class="node-inner">

  
      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/node/99" title="Using Velocity as SiteMesh decorator with Spring framework">Using Velocity as SiteMesh decorator with Spring framework</a>
    </h2>
  
  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
          Submitted by Colin Sampaleanu on Mon, 2005-01-24 18:00        </div>
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"> in <ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_6 first last active"><a href="/presentations" rel="tag" title="A link to a technical article about Spring" class="active">Technical Article</a></li>
</ul></div>
          </div>
  
  <div class="content">
    <p><a href="http://www.jroller.com/page/timosinko/20050124#using_velocity_as_sitemesh_decorator" target="_self">This detailed blog entry</a> by Wang Qi describes one approach to combining the use of SiteMesh (the page decoration library), Velocity and Spring.</p><p>Update 2005-5-20: <a href="http://forum.springframework.org/viewtopic.php?p=22560" target="_self">this forum thread</a> goes into the same topic. There may be easier ways to do this with newer SiteMesh versions.&nbsp;</p>  </div>

  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment_comments first last"><a href="/node/99#comments" title="Jump to the first comment of this posting.">2 comments</a></li>
</ul>
